Normal Linear Model.

####Fitting the model The Aim of the linear model is to predict the final (G3) score. Let’s start to construct a scatter diagram of the G3 score

studentdata1$school <- as.factor(studentdata1$school)
plot(studentdata1$failures, studentdata1$G3,xlab = "Number of failures",ylab = "G3 score")

plot(studentdata1$age, studentdata1$G3,xlab = "Age",ylab = "G3 score")

plot(studentdata1$absences, studentdata1$G3,xlab = "Number of absences",ylab = "G3 score")

For the linear model, we will use 3 predictors to predict the students final grade. The predictors are: - Past class failures - Age - Absences

 linmod1<- glm(G3~failures + age + absences,family="gaussian",data = studentdata1)
summary(linmod1)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = G3 ~ failures + age + absences, family = "gaussian", 
##     data = studentdata1)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -6.5443  -2.0721  -0.2804   2.2115   8.5817  
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 13.70737    2.21100   6.200 1.58e-09 ***
## failures    -1.24869    0.25090  -4.977 1.01e-06 ***
## age         -0.08571    0.13459  -0.637  0.52463    
## absences    -0.06597    0.02029  -3.252  0.00126 ** 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

## Residual deviance: 3276  on 353  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 1814.5
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 2

From this, we get the best estimate of the trendline which we call the regression line. The coefficients have been determined for the 3 predictors, hence

G3 ~ Normal(13.70737 -1.24869 x failures - 0.08571 x age - 0.06597 x absences,3.04639147189)

To check the suitability of this model, we start to look at the residuals against each of the predictors to make sure the spread of data points looks even and regular across the plot.

Evaluating the Model

plot(studentdata1$failures,linmod1$residuals,main = "residuals vs Failures",xlab = "Number of failed classes",ylab = "residuals")

plot(studentdata1$age,linmod1$residuals,main = "residuals vs age",xlab = "Age",ylab = "residuals")

plot(studentdata1$absences,linmod1$residuals,main = "residuals vs absences",xlab = "Number of absences",ylab = "residuals")

From the residual graphs, we construct a histogram of the residuals.We should expect a Gaussian curve.

hist(linmod1$residuals)

This means that the choice of “gaussian” distribution is suitable and so we construct a Q-Q plot.

qqnorm(linmod1$residuals)

Apart from a few points on the ends points of the q-q plot. The observed distribution looks appropriate and the final model can be written as

G3 ~ Normal(13.70737 -1.24869 x failures - 0.08571 x age - 0.06597 x absences,3.04639147189)

Logistic Model

Predict if a student attended nursery based on gender,family size,mothers education,fathers education and cohabitation status.

To start this logistic model, we must first assign binary variables to the nursery variable Assign 0 for didn’t attend nursery 1 for attend nursery

#create new variable Bnursery
studentdata1$Bnursery[studentdata1$nursery == "no"]<- 0
studentdata1$Bnursery[studentdata1$nursery == "yes"]<- 1


nursery.mod <- glm(studentdata1$Bnursery ~ sex + famsize + Medu + Fedu + Pstatus, family = binomial, data =studentdata1)

We use the summary function to see which of the predictors significantly predict whether or not a student attended nursery.

summary(nursery.mod)
